# Burst search profile
#
# Holds at a quiet baseline (20 req/s) for 1 minute to warm up, then spikes
# to 150 req/s for 30 seconds (the burst), holds at 150 for another 30 seconds,
# then recovers back to 20 req/s over 30 seconds and holds for 2 minutes.
#
# Use this to observe:
#   - Whether the Capture Proxy recovers gracefully after a search burst (no
#     stuck connections, latency returns to baseline after burst ends)
#   - Agg query latency degradation during the spike — aggs are the most
#     expensive operation and will breach p95 thresholds first
#   - k6 "dropped_iterations" counter — if VUs can't keep up with 150 req/s,
#     iterations are dropped and logged in the k6 terminal summary
#
# NOTE: p95 latency thresholds WILL likely breach during the 150 req/s spike
# (that is the point). k6 will exit non-zero. Use Grafana to inspect the
# time-series behaviour rather than relying on the exit code for pass/fail.
#
# Total test duration: 4 minutes 30 seconds.

CAPTURE_PROXY_URL=https://capture-proxy:9200
EXECUTOR=ramping-arrival-rate
RAMP_STAGES=[{"duration":"1m","target":20},{"duration":"30s","target":150},{"duration":"30s","target":150},{"duration":"30s","target":20},{"duration":"2m","target":20}]

SEARCH_VUS=60
SEARCH_MAX_VUS=200

SEED_DOC_COUNT=100000
DEEP_PAGING_ENABLED=false
CONNECTION_MODE=pinned
